tips for final exams
(to become a good test-taker)
videos.voice_over:
tips for final exams
(to become a good test-taker)
I'm in college who's taking like 40 finals and considers yourself a very good test-taker. Here are my ultimate final exam hacks. Keep these in the back of your mind so that you can become a good test taker.
Tip number one, if you're doing a multiple choice and you hit a question that feels confusing, just go with your gut. Mark it, move on, and come back to it later because sometimes the answer will come up later in the exam. I think I do this in probably every single exam.
Tip number two is use study fetch to prep yourself to take exams. Study fetch makes quizzes slash exams directly from your notes so that you know what areas you're weaker in so you can actually tackle these and solve these areas before you're actually in the exam room.
You can also time yourself and know how long you take per question.
Tip three is be super intentional with the food you take before your exam. This is so important. People often overlook this. One hour before your exam, skip the sugar and the energy drinks. You need to eat brain nourishing foods like blueberries, dark chocolate, or nuts that you're feeding your focus.
Tip four, if your final has short answer questions, skim back to the multiple choice. Sometimes it'll help you infer the answer from similar wording.
And tip five, pay attention to the point, especially in math or like number based courses. If a question is worth like several points, just give it your best guess and write something down because you at least might get half of the points or some of the points if you hit some of the marks.
If you want more exam tips, just comment down below and I'll make a part two.

videos.voice_over: oh my god my exam's tomorrow and I haven't even started. okay we're good. I got you. I only studied for an hour and a half the morning of my exam and here's what I got. here's my foolproof method and it's only three steps. First of all, do not go through your slides and reread your notes until you get it. 'cause you're not that doesn't teach you effectively and chances are you already subconsciously know half of the information. Step one is to pick out what you don't know. You have to do some kind of practice test for this. I upload my class material to Knowt and turn it into a practice test about everything covered in class. When you submit the test, it will tell you what you get wrong and that's what you're going to focus on. Okay, number two, make yourself uncomfortable and drink something cold. I'll explain. The cold temperature will shock your brain so you don't lose focus and the uncomfortable environment will discourage you from scrolling. It's proven that you're more likely to lose focus when you're in comfortable environments like your bed. So do the opposite. That means studying on the floor or a hard chair and sipping on something that will give you almost a brain freeze. If you maintain these two things while studying, it will also help with your information retention because you're involving the thalamus into the memory encoding process. Okay, finally number three, when you study, do it in little pieces. View a third or a fourth of the chapter, then quiz yourself on it right after with the same practice test. Reviewing the material familiarizes it, then using active recall techniques like the practice tests will solidify it. But do not do it all at once. A bonus hack that is that I reframe all of the information into gossip or storytelling. You can do this with literally any topic and this humanizes the information. Your brain prefers a juicy plot over bullet points. I know that sounds silly, but that's actually how we've evolved to process information. Anyway, that's all I have for now 'cause I have to go study more, but if you like this at all, follow me 'cause I post these every single day.

And even if filters out in the last 24 hours, you still get 100 applicants before you've even seen it, cause they are way too saturated. So instead you need to be using niche job boards and advanced Google searches to find those remote opportunities. Cause if you're qualified for the job, then speed wins this game. I built a massive list of 500 job boards and resources completely for free that you can use. So save this video and screenshot this. And this is a list of remote job boards that I found. You have some popular ones like Remote OK, but there's other ones in here that you've probably never even heard of. I'm also hosting a free training session next Sunday about how the job market has changed for remote workers, and I'm going to show you step-by-step how to actually get hired in 2026. Because if you're still scrolling through LinkedIn, Indeed, and you're still getting rejection after rejection, you are gonna be completely cooked, especially with the rise of AI that employers are using to filter out candidates. For generations, we've been sold a singular vision of career success‚Äîgo to school, get a degree, land a job, and climb the corporate ladder. This linear trajectory has been presented as a safe, conservative path to professional achievement. By developing multiple skill sets and gaining exposure to different environments, those with non-linear careers often experience richer professional and personal growth. For example, diversifying your income streams creates more financial freedom. These varied experiences create a unique perspective that traditional careers rarely provide.

When your career isn't locked into a single track, you can adapt as life unfolds around you. The flexibility of a non-linear career path means you can continuously recalibrate your work to align with what matters most to you at different life stages.
